# Git push — user terminal only

When the user asks to push (or says "push", "push to origin", "push and wait for CI", etc.):

- Do **NOT** run `git push`, `git push -u`, or any remote push command from the agent shell.
- You **may** still stage, commit, and verify locally (`git status`, `git diff`, `git log`, tests, lint).
- After commits are ready, give the user the exact commands to run in **their own terminal** (IDE terminal or external), where their GitHub credentials are configured.
- Tell them to run the push there so GitHub attributes the push to them.
- Wait for the user to confirm the push succeeded before checking CI or continuing.

Example handoff:

```bash
git push -u origin <branch>
```

Do not push on their behalf even if you have shell access and it would "just work."
